Real-Life Analogy

Imagine you are a security guard.

with sharing → "I will always follow the company's security rules."
without sharing → "I will ignore the security rules."
inherited sharing → "I'll do whatever my manager tells me."

So, inherited sharing has no opinion of its own.


Example 1 - Called from a with sharing class
public with sharing class AccountController {

    public static void getAccounts() {
        AccountService.getAccounts();
    }
}

Service class

public inherited sharing class AccountService {

    public static void getAccounts() {

        List<Account> accounts = [
            SELECT Id, Name
            FROM Account
        ];

        System.debug(accounts);
    }
}
Suppose

OWD = Private

Accounts

Admin owns
-----------
Google
Microsoft

Sales User owns
---------------
Apple

Current user = Sales User

Execution

AccountController
(with sharing)

        ↓

AccountService
(inherited sharing)

Since the caller is with sharing, the service also behaves as with sharing.

Result

Apple

Only one record is returned.


Example 2 - Called from a without sharing class

Controller

public without sharing class AdminController {

    public static void getAccounts() {
        AccountService.getAccounts();
    }
}

Service

public inherited sharing class AccountService {

    public static void getAccounts() {

        List<Account> accounts = [
            SELECT Id, Name
            FROM Account
        ];

        System.debug(accounts);
    }
}

Execution

AdminController
(without sharing)

        ↓

AccountService
(inherited sharing)

Now the service becomes without sharing.

Result

Google
Microsoft
Apple

All records are returned.

Same Service Class, Different Results

Notice that we didn't change the AccountService class at all.

public inherited sharing class AccountService

The only thing that changed was who called it.

| Caller            | Service behaves as |
| ----------------- | ------------------ |
| `with sharing`    | `with sharing`     |
| `without sharing` | `without sharing`  |


That's why it's called inherited sharing—it inherits the caller's sharing mode.

======================
Easy Trick to Remember
=======================

with sharing
↓
"I will always respect record sharing."

without sharing
↓
"I will always ignore record sharing."

inherited sharing
↓
"I will do whatever my caller/manager is doing."



Interview Question :-

Q: Why not simply use with sharing everywhere?

Answer: Because some service classes are reused by different entry points. One caller may need to respect sharing, while another trusted process (such as an admin utility) may intentionally run without sharing. inherited sharing allows the same service class to work correctly in both scenarios without duplicating code.


